05893nam a22011535i 9780520913707DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209137077 a10.1525/97805209137072doi  a(DE-B1597)544119  a(OCoLC)1149422343  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS595b.L33 1991eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a615.8/82/0959512201 aLaderman, Carol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaming the Wind of Desire :bPsychology, Medicine, and Aesthetics in Malay Shamanistic Performance /cCarol Laderman.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (386 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Studies of Health Systems and Medical Care ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tPART I. MALAY MEDICINE, MALAY PERSON -- t1. An Introduction to Malay Shamanism -- t2. Islamic Humoralism on the Malay Peninsula -- t3. "Unusual" Illnesses -- t4. Angin: the Inner Winds -- t5. The Performance of Healing -- tPART II. RITUAL DRAMAS OF HEALING -- t6. A Stifled Talent -- t7. Seance for a Sick Shaman -- t8. Breaking Contracts with the Spirit World -- tPART III. AFTERWORD -- t9. Words and Meaning -- tAPPENDIX A. A SHAMAN SPEAKS -- tAPPENDIX B. MUSIC OF THE MAIN PETERI -- tGLOSSARY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCharged with restoring harmony and relieving pain, the Malay shaman places his patients in trance and encourages them to express their talents, drives, personality traits—the "Inner Winds" of Malay medical lore—in a kind of performance. These healing ceremonies, formerly viewed by Western anthropologists as exotic curiosities, actually reveal complex multicultural origins and a unique indigenous medical tradition whose psychological content is remarkably relevant to contemporary Western concerns.Accepted as apprentice to a Malay shaman, Carol Laderman learned and recorded every aspect of the healing seance and found it comparable in many ways to the traditional dramas of Southeast Asia and of other cultures such as ancient Greece, Japan, and India. The Malay seance is a total performance, complete with audience, stage, props, plot, music, and dance. The players include the patient along with the shaman and his troupe. At the center of the drama are pivotal relationships—among people, between humans and spirits, and within the self. The best of the Malay shamans are superb poets, dramatists, and performers as well as effective healers of body and soul.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropology. 0aCulture. 0aEthnology. 0aHumanities. 0aMalays (Asian people)xMedicine. 0aMalays (Asian people)xReligion. 0aMalays (Asian people)zMalaysiazKampung Mercang (Terengganu)xMedicine. 0aMalays (Asian people)zMalaysiazKampung Mercang (Terengganu)xReligion. 0aMedicinexReligious aspects. 0aPsychology and religion. 0aReligion. 0aShamanismzMalaysiazKampong Merchang (Terengganu). 0aShamanismzMalaysiazKampung Mercang (Terengganu). 0aShamanism. 0aSocial sciences. 0aTherapeutics. 0aTraditional medicinezMalaysiazKampong Merchang (Terengganu). 0aTraditional medicinezMalaysiazKampung Mercang (Terengganu). 0aTraditional medicine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aancient greece.  aanthropology.  abody and soul.  acomparative studies of health systems and medical care.  aharmony.  ahealing ceremony.  ahealing seance.  ahealing.  ahumans and spirits.  aillness.  aindia.  aindigenous medical tradition.  aindigenous peoples.  ainner winds.  aisl